---
import PageShell from '../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const title = "Insurance for International Electrical Engineers | Compare Expat Plans";
const description = "Health insurance guide for Electrical Engineers working internationally, covering engineering positions abroad, power and electronics careers, and global electrical engineering opportunities.";
const headline = "Insurance for International Electrical Engineers";
const subheadline = "Coverage solutions for Electrical Engineers working abroad, designing electrical systems internationally, and pursuing careers across power, electronics, and technology companies worldwide.";
const canonicalPath = "/guides/electrical-engineer-insurance";
const heroBackgroundImage = "/images/guides/electrical-engineer-insurance-hero.png";

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'overview', label: 'Overview' },
  { id: 'coverage-needs', label: 'Coverage Needs' },
  { id: 'work-settings', label: 'Work Settings' },
  { id: 'credentials', label: 'Credentials' },
  { id: 'occupational-health', label: 'Occupational Health' },
  { id: 'work-demands', label: 'Work Demands' },
  { id: 'career-considerations', label: 'Career Considerations' },
  { id: 'faqs', label: 'FAQs' },
  { id: 'next-steps', label: 'Next Steps' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title={title}
  description={description}
  headline={headline}
  subheadline={subheadline}
  canonicalPath={canonicalPath}
  heroBackgroundImage={heroBackgroundImage}
  tocItems={tocItems}
>
  <article class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">

    <section id="overview">
      <h2>International Electrical Engineer Careers</h2>
      <p>
        Electrical Engineers design, develop, and maintain electrical systems including power generation, electronics, control systems, and telecommunications. International electrical engineering offers opportunities to work on global power infrastructure, technology development, and electronics manufacturing worldwide.
      </p>
      <p>
        International electrical engineering opportunities exist through power utilities, electronics manufacturers, technology companies, and the universal need for electrical systems expertise across industries.
      </p>
      <p>
        This guide addresses insurance considerations for Electrical Engineers working abroad across power, electronics, and technology companies worldwide.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="coverage-needs">
      <h2>Coverage Needs for Electrical Engineers</h2>

      <ComparisonTable
        columns={[
          { key: 'need', header: 'Coverage Need' },
          { key: 'why', header: 'Why It Matters' },
          { key: 'typical', header: 'Coverage Situation?' },
        ]}
        rows={[
          { need: 'General health coverage', why: 'Professional health maintenance', typical: 'Usually employer-provided' },
          { need: 'Eye coverage', why: 'Circuit design and detailed work', typical: 'Important for profession' },
          { need: 'Travel coverage', why: 'Site visits and installations', typical: 'Often needed' },
          { need: 'Physical coverage', why: 'Field work and site presence', typical: 'Consider for role' },
          { need: 'Ergonomic coverage', why: 'CAD and simulation work', typical: 'Consider including' },
          { need: 'Mental health support', why: 'Project complexity and deadlines', typical: 'Often included' },
        ]}
      />

      <h3>Design and Field Work</h3>
      <p>
        Electrical engineering involves both detailed design work and field-based installation and testing. Design work creates eye strain from circuit diagrams and simulation. Field work involves travel, physical activity, and exposure to industrial environments. Coverage should address both contexts.
      </p>
      <p>
        Power engineers particularly may work at generation facilities, substations, and distribution infrastructure requiring travel and physical presence at industrial sites.
      </p>

      <h3>Safety Considerations</h3>
      <p>
        While engineers typically work with systems in controlled conditions, electrical hazards exist in field work. Employers provide safety training and equipment. Standard health coverage addresses potential workplace incidents.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="work-settings">
      <h2>Coverage by Work Setting</h2>

      <h3>Power/Utility</h3>
      <p>
        Power generation or utility company. Strong utility benefits. Infrastructure focus. Utilities offer stability.
      </p>

      <h3>Electronics Manufacturer</h3>
      <p>
        Electronics or semiconductor company. Tech sector benefits. Product development. Electronics offer innovation.
      </p>

      <h3>Consulting Engineering</h3>
      <p>
        Electrical engineering consultancy. Professional services benefits. Client variety. Consulting offers breadth.
      </p>

      <h3>Technology Company</h3>
      <p>
        Tech company hardware. Premium tech benefits. Product focus. Tech offers resources.
      </p>

      <h3>Industrial</h3>
      <p>
        Manufacturing or industrial company. Corporate benefits. Plant systems. Industrial offers stability.
      </p>
    </section>

    <CTABox
      title="Coverage for Electrical Engineers"
      description="Compare international health plans designed for Electrical Engineers working abroad across power, electronics, and technology companies worldwide."
      buttonText="Compare Electrical Engineer Plans"
      buttonHref="/"
      variant="highlight"
    />

    <section id="credentials">
      <h2>Credentials and Professional Recognition</h2>

      <h3>PE License</h3>
      <p>
        Professional Engineer license. Required for some roles. Country-specific requirements.
      </p>

      <h3>Engineering Degree</h3>
      <p>
        Electrical engineering degree. Accredited program. Foundation credential.
      </p>

      <h3>Certifications</h3>
      <p>
        Industry-specific certifications. Control systems, power systems. Value varies by specialty.
      </p>

      <h3>Experience</h3>
      <p>
        System experience. Industry expertise. Project delivery. Experience highly valued.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="occupational-health">
      <h2>Occupational Health Considerations</h2>

      <h3>Eye Strain</h3>
      <p>
        Circuit design. Detailed schematics. Screen work. Eye coverage important.
      </p>

      <h3>Field Work</h3>
      <p>
        Site visits. Installation support. Testing activities. Physical coverage relevant.
      </p>

      <h3>Design Work</h3>
      <p>
        Computer-based design. Extended sessions. Simulation work. Ergonomic coverage valuable.
      </p>

      <h3>Project Complexity</h3>
      <p>
        System complexity. Integration challenges. Deadline pressure. Mental health support helpful.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="work-demands">
      <h2>Managing Work Demands</h2>

      <h3>System Design</h3>
      <p>
        Circuit design. Power systems. Control systems. Design is core work.
      </p>

      <h3>Analysis</h3>
      <p>
        Simulation. Load analysis. Testing verification. Analysis validates design.
      </p>

      <h3>Implementation</h3>
      <p>
        Installation support. Commissioning. Troubleshooting. Implementation delivers systems.
      </p>

      <h3>Documentation</h3>
      <p>
        Technical documentation. Specifications. As-built drawings. Documentation supports operation.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="career-considerations">
      <h2>Career Considerations</h2>

      <h3>Growing Demand</h3>
      <p>
        Electrification expanding. Renewable energy growing. Electronics essential. Demand strong.
      </p>

      <h3>Career Paths</h3>
      <p>
        Senior engineer. Engineering manager. Technical director. Executive leadership. Multiple paths.
      </p>

      <h3>Credential Portability</h3>
      <p>
        Engineering degree recognized. PE requirements vary. Experience valued. Credentials portable.
      </p>

      <h3>Technology Evolution</h3>
      <p>
        Renewable integration. Smart systems. Power electronics. Technology evolving rapidly.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="faqs">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="space-y-6">
        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">I'm an electrical engineer considering international work. What should I know?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            Employers typically provide benefits. Power and tech offer strong packages. Experience valued globally.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">Do employers provide international coverage?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            Utilities and tech companies yes. Consulting firms vary. Benefits typically comprehensive. Verify specific offer.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">Is eye coverage important?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            Yes for detailed work. Circuit design demands visual precision. Screen time intensive. Eye coverage valuable.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">Do electrical engineering credentials transfer internationally?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            Degree recognized globally. PE requirements vary. Experience valued universally. Credentials transfer well.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">Should I consider travel coverage?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            Depends on role. Power engineers often travel. Electronics may be office-based. Role determines need.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">What's the career outlook?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            Electrification driving demand. Renewable energy growing. Electronics essential. Outlook excellent.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="next-steps">
      <h2>Next Steps</h2>
      <p>
        Start by evaluating employer benefits packages. Consider eye coverage for design work. Include travel coverage if field-based. Verify international coverage scope for your role.
      </p>
      <p>
        Electrical Engineers power systems worldwide. Your coverage should support electrical engineering careers—addressing design and field demands, covering health maintenance, and protecting you across electrical engineering work worldwide.
      </p>
    </section>

    <CTABox
      title="Protect Your Engineering Career"
      description="Compare international health plans designed for Electrical Engineers working abroad across power, electronics, and technology companies worldwide."
      buttonText="Compare Plans Now"
      buttonHref="/"
      variant="highlight"
    />

  </article>
</PageShell>
